ille","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: variant of   Bonneville   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Bonneville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Francois, Liette, Normand, Pierre.","French: habitational name from any of numerous places called Bonneville, from Old French <i>bonne</i> ‘good’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. Compare   Bonville  .","Altered form of French <b>Bonnevialle</b>: habitational name from Bonnevialle in the central part of France."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese (<b>Ōi</b>): written 大井 ‘large well’. It is found in central and eastern Japan.","Japanese (<b>Ōi</b>): written 多 ‘many’. It was pronounced <b>Oho</b> in ancient times and is listed in the <i>Shinsen shōjiroku</i>. It is not common in modern Japan.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 黃, see   Huang   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Huang","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Wei, Ming, Jian, Ying, Yi, Jing, Wen, Jin, Ping, Min, Yong, Cheng, Hong, Chong, Chang, Pao, Sha, Shen, Tun, You, Chung, Shiu, Ti, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 黄, meaning ‘yellow’ in Chinese: (i) from Huang (黃), the name of an ancient state (present-day Huangchuan in Henan province)annexed by the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) traced back to some minority ethnic groups in ancient southern China."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Bosville of Oxmuir was born in 1290, in Berwickshire, Scotland, his father, William de Bosville of Oxmuir, was 48 and his mother, Lady Christina Murry, was 45. He died in 1335, in Scotland, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1290–1335":"1290–1335","1301–Female":"1301–Surnud","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1321–1366":"1321–1366","1242–1292":"1242–1292","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1335":"1335","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1366":"1366","1321":"1321","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1292":"1292","1 January 1321":"1. jaanuar 1321","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Oxmuir, Scotland":"Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland","Oxmuir, Hume Par, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Hume, Berwickshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1290–1335":"1290–1335","1301–Female":"1301–Kuollut","1280–1340":"1280–